'''''Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer''''' (English: ''Who Said Yesterday'') is a compilation album released by Guatemalan singer-songwriter [[Ricardo Arjona]] on August 21, 2007. Dan Warner and Lee Levin co-produced the album under their stage name Los Gringos, together with Arjona and Puerto Rican singer-songwriter [[Tommy Torres]]. It was recorded in the United States, Mexico, Italy and Argentina, and is the last album Arjona released under the [[Sony Music Entertainment]] label before signing with [[Warner Music Group]].

The album is Arjona's first compilation to include new material in the form of re-recorded versions of past hits in different musical genres from the original recordings. Arjona said ''Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer'' is "a disc that started as an experiment" and "finished being very complicated". It features guest artists such as [[Marc Anthony]], [[Marta S<U+00E1>nchez]] and Mexican [[Ska music|ska]] band [[Pante<U+00F3>n Rococ<U+00F3>]], among others. Critically and commercially successful, ''Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer'' topped the US [[Latin Pop Albums]] chart and reached number two on the [[Top Latin Albums]] chart. The album became a hit in Latin America, receiving [[Gold certification]]s in Venezuela, Uruguay, Colombia, Chile and Peru, and [[Platinum certification]]s in Argentina, Mexico and the United States (Latin).

The album spawned two commercially successful singles, "[[Qui<U+00E9>n]]" and "[[Quiero (Ricardo Arjona song)|Quiero]]". For most of his career, Arjona was signed to Sony Music, and later, [[Sony BMG]]; he signed a long-term recording deal with [[Warner Music Latina]] in September 2008, which made ''Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer'' the last original album Arjona released under Sony. ''Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer'' was nominated in 2008 for the [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Album]] and the Best Male Pop Vocal Album at the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]].

== Background ==
In a press conference, Arjona stated that "yesterday is the cumulus of this that put us here, which raised us and made us what we are, for good or bad."<ref name="Barcenas">Cruz B<U+00E1>rcenas, Arturo (22 November 2007). [http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2007/11/22/index.php?section=espectaculos&article=a14n1esp "''Qui<U+00E9>n dijo ayer'', un disco dif<U+00ED>cil sobre el pasado"]. La Jornada ([[Universidad Nacional Aut<U+00F3>noma de Mexico]]). Desarrollo de Medios, S.A. Retrieved on 12 May 2012.</ref> He also said that ''Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer'' was more than a compilation, and that "it's an album with all the features of the typical greatest hits disc. Several songs are the most popular, but others are the most important on other topics. We've dressed them different. "Se Nos Muere El Amor" is now with piano and flauta, as an example."<ref name="Barcenas"/> He further stated that it was "an album that begun as an experiment, with a dose of informality, and suddenly, when I realized of what the producers were achieving with the songs I worked many years ago, the album finished as being very complicated."<ref name="Barcenas"/>

After spending the majority of his career signed to [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony]], and later, [[Sony BMG]], Arjona signed a long-term recording deal with [[Warner Music Latina]] in September 2008.<ref name=leila1>Cobo, Leila (22 September 2008). [http://www.billboard.com/news/ricardo-arjona-signs-with-warner-music-latina-1003853422.story#/news/ricardo-arjona-signs-with-warner-music-latina-1003853422.story "Ricardo Arjona Signs With Warner Music Latina"]. ''Billboard''. Nielsen Business Media. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> I<U+00F1>igo Zabala, chairman of [[Warner Music Latina|Warner Music Latin America]] commented that "He's an artist that fits perfectly with our company," and that "We are a label that has a major catalog of songwriters and quality pop and rock from the likes of Man<U+00E1>, Alejandro Sanz, Laura Pausini, and now, Arjona."<ref name=leila1/> This departure made ''Quien Dijo Ayer'' the last album the artist directly released on his former label, although Sony later released another album named ''[[Simplemente Lo Mejor]]''.<ref>Later in 2008, Sony released a greatest-hits compilation named ''[[Simplemente Lo Mejor]]'', but Arjona had already released ''[[5to Piso]]'' on Warner Music.</ref>

== Composition ==
[[File:Marc Anthony 2009 White House.jpg|thumb|200px|left|[[Marc Anthony]] sang along Arjona on the [[Salsa music|salsa version]] of "Historia de Taxi".]]
For this compilation album, Arjona re-recorded some of his older songs in a different style from the original versions, and remastered others. "Si El Norte Fuera El Sur" was transformed into a [[Ska music|ska]]-style song, which he performed with [[Pante<U+00F3>n Rococ<U+00F3>]].<ref name=qdaallmusic>Birchmeier, Jason. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/quin-dijo-ayer-r1184550/review "Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer > Review""]. [[Allmusic]]. Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> Argentinian jazz musician [[Fernando Otero]] was featured on the new version of "Jes<U+00FA>s, Verbo No Sustantivo".<ref>[http://www.am.com.mx/Nota.aspx?ID=134456&strPlaza=Leon&IDPlaza=1 "Festeja Arjona con sus fans en NY"]. Periodico A.M. Retrieved on May 5, 2012.</ref> "Historia De Taxi" was transformed into a salsa song, which Arjona performed with American singer [[Marc Anthony]]<ref name=qdaallmusic/> and pianist [[Sergio George]];<ref>[http://www.adnmundo.com/contenidos/adncool/ricardo_arjona_quien_dijo_ayer_co190707.html "Ricardo Arjona: cuenta regresiva para la salida de <U+00BF>Qui<U+00E9>n dijo ayer?"]. ADN Mundo.  Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> George said, "It's been interesting to work with two figures from different music worlds on the interest of making good music.",<ref name="sergio">[http://www.tabascohoy.com/noticia.php?id_nota=137145 "Graban Ricardo Arjona y Marc Anthony tema a d<U+00FA>o"]. Tabasco Hoy. Retrieved on May 2, 2012.</ref> and that "every time a reunion of this kind happens, it [is] a reason to celebrate."<ref name="sergio"/> 

Arjona also re-recorded "Realmente No Estoy Tan Solo"with singer [[Sandro de Am<U+00E9>rica|Sandro]]; it was last song recorded by Sandro, who died in 4 January 2010.<ref name=lagaceta>[http://www.lagaceta.com.ar/nota/359604/Espect%C3%A1culos/Hoy_respira_mejor_nunca.html "Hoy respira mejor que nunca"]. La Gaceta.  Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> Arjona's manager told Argentinian newspaper [[Clar<U+00ED>n]] that "[the singer] had the idea of inviting Roberto [Sandro] for his album, he [Sandro] showed enthusiasm and manifested the same degree of appreciation to Arjona. It seemed to him that he [Arjona] was an artist who proclaims the same values he proclaimed."<ref>[http://www.adnmundo.com/contenidos/adncool/ricardo_arjona_sandro_quien_dijo_ayer_co230807.html "Ricardo Arjona: se confirma que grab<U+00F3> un tema junto a Sandro"]. ADN Mundo. Retrieved on 5 May 2012.</ref>

This album included three new songs. "[[Qui<U+00E9>n]]" was written by Arjona, who co-produced it with Tommy Torres.<ref name=adnmundo2>[http://www.adnmundo.com/contenidos/adncool/ricardo_arjona_quien_nuevo_disco_co100707.html "Ricardo Arjona habla de su nueva canci<U+00F3>n"]. ADN Mundo.  Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> It was released as the [[lead single]] from the album on 19 June 2007.<ref>[http://itunes.apple.com/us/album/quien-single/id257590898 "Qui<U+00E9>n - Single by Ricardo Arjona"]. iTunes (US). Apple, Inc. Retrieved on 2 May 2012.</ref> Arjona commented that "'Qui<U+00E9>n' is the world out of the window and the prison built by ourselves. It's the freedom to chose the path or to prefer loneliness as an argument of nostalgia. 'Qui<U+00E9>n' is a story with the hurry of the desperate, is the flashback of those who end up loving alone."<ref name="PEE">[http://www.peopleenespanol.com/article/escucha-el-nuevo-tema-de-ricardo-arjona-quien "Escucha el nuevo tema de Ricardo Arjona: "Qui<U+00E9>n""]. People en Espa<U+00F1>ol. Retrieved on 2 May 2012.</ref><ref name="Emol">[http://www.emol.com/noticias/magazine/2007/06/20/259887/arjona-lanza-cancion-con-mas-poesia-romantica.html "Arjona lanza canci<U+00F3>n con m<U+00E1>s poes<U+00ED>a rom<U+00E1>ntica"]. El Mercurio Online. Retrieved on 2 May 2012.</ref> "[[Quiero]]", also written by Arjona, was released as the second single in November 2007. Website ADN Mundo called the song bohemian and hippie, and that it was "a love story that doesn't speak about love, but instead about the recent events on the world we live [in] and finally comes to the search of an individual who challenges nostalgia finding entertainment on the impossible."<ref>[http://www.adnmundo.com/contenidos/actualidad/arjona_nuevo_disco_quien_250807.html "Ricardo Arjona volvi<U+00F3> con disco nuevo, y viejos temas"]. ADN Mundo. Retrieved on 2 May 2012.</ref> In 2009, "Quiero" was awarded the Pop/Ballad Songs of the Year award by the [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]].<ref>[http://www.ascap.com/eventsawards/awards/latinawards/2009/pop.aspx "17th Annual El Premio ASCAP 2009 - Pop/Ballad"].  [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]]. Retrieved on March 24, 2012.</ref> The third new song on the album was "Espantap<U+00E1>jaros", which was written by Arjona and Miguel Luna.<ref>
[http://www.ascap.com/ace/search.cfm?requesttimeout=300&mode=results&searchstr=351433559%20&search_in=i&search_type=exact&search_det=t,s,w,p,b,v&results_pp=25&start=1 "ACE Title Search"]. [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]]. Retrieved on 8 May 2012.</ref>

== Release and promotion ==
''Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer'' was released in most markets as a two-disc compilation album. The first disc contains sixteen songs, of which thirteen are new versions of Arjona's past hits. On this disc appears the duets with Pante<U+00F3>n Rococ<U+00F3> on "Si El Norte Fuera El Sur"; Marc Anthony on "Historia de Taxi"; Marta Sanchez on "Tarde (Sin Da<U+00F1>os A Terceros)"; [[Eros Ramazzoti]] on "A Ti" and Sandro de Am<U+00E9>rica on "Realmente No Estoy Tan Solo".<ref name="booklet">Taken from the album's two-disc edition booklet.''Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer'' [two-disc edition] (booklet). [[Ricardo Arjona]]. Norte, a division of [[Sony Music Entertainment]]. 8869 711335 2. 2007.</ref> This disc also contains the new songs "Qui<U+00E9>n", "Quiero" and "Espantap<U+00E1>jaros". The second disc contains the same songs as the first disc but in their original versions, remastered.<ref name="booklet"/>

In Canada, Germany, Brazil and Mexico, a digital special edition was released<ref name="spetbra"/> that features only six songs on the second digital disc instead of 13.<ref name="spetmex"/><ref name="spetcan"/> The songs included on the second disc on this version were "Se Nos Muere El Amor", "Dime Que No", "Si El Norte Fuera El Sur", "A Ti", "Tu Reputaci<U+00F3>n" and "Cuando".<ref name="spetger"/> This Brazilian version featured a different cover art.<ref name="spetbra"/> The album was also released as a single disc version with only the new versions and songs.

Also, in Mexico, two physical single-disc versions of the album were released. The first includes the first single from ''[[5to Piso|Quinto Piso]]'', "[[Como Duele]]" as a bonus track.<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/quin-dijo-ayer-r2168197 Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer - Ricardo Arjona]. ''Allmusic''. Retrieved 19-09-2011.</ref> This version was also released in Spain.<ref name="QDA-Spain">[http://itunes.apple.com/es/album/quien-dijo-ayer/id339686006 "Quien Dijo Ayer de Ricardo Arjona"]. iTunes. Apple, inc. Retrieved on May 4, 2012.</ref> The second version does not include "Espantap<U+00E1>jaros" or "Realmente No Estoy Tan Solo"; it also includes "[[Como Duele]]" as a bonus track.<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/quin-dijo-ayer-r2274739 Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer - Ricardo Arjona]. ''Allmusic''. Retrieved 19 September 2011.</ref>

=== Singles ===
The first single released from the album was "Qui<U+00E9>n", a Latin pop song written by Arjona and produced by Tommy Torres and Los Gringos. The song charted on the [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] [[Latin Songs]] at number twenty-one, and reached its peak the week ending 25 August 2007.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/ricardo-arjona/chart-history/29908?f=363&g=Singles "Ricardo Arjona Album & Song Chart History"]. Billboard. Retrieved on 2 May 2012.</ref> The song was more successful on the [[Latin Pop Songs]] chart, where it reached number four. The music video for "Qui<U+00E9>n" was filmed in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]].<ref name="PEE"/> The second single released was "Quiero", which reached number twelve on the ''Billboard'' Latin Songs chart, and number eight on the Latin Pop Songs component chart. "Quiero" was very popular in Central American countries like Honduras, Nicaragua and Panam<U+00E1>.<ref>[http://www.ppn.com.py/html/noticias/noticia-ver.asp?id=40839 "Ricardo Arjona dice "Quiero" en la cima diez primeros de Ritmoson Latino"]. RPP. Retrieved on 2 May 2012.</ref> The music video for "Quiero" was filmed in the Dominican Republic and premiered in November 2007.<ref name="Quiero_Vid"> [http://www.adnmundo.com/contenidos/adncool/ricardo_arjona_quiero_quien_dijo_ayer_co221007.html "Arjona ya tiene listo su nuevo video"]. ADN Mundo. Retrieved on 2 May 2012.</ref>

==Reception==

=== Critical response ===
{{Album ratings
| rev1 = [[Allmusic]] 
| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name="birchmeier">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1184550|pure_url=yes}}|title= Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer > Review| first=Jason|last=Birchmeier |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref>
}}
Jason Birchmeier from [[Allmusic]] gave a positive review of the album, and commented that, "while only a couple of the new versions depart stylistically from the originals, the contemporary productions breathe new life into these songs, which should be well known by longtime fans."<ref name="birchmeier"/>

=== Commercial performance ===
''Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer'' was Arjona's second album after ''[[Galer<U+00ED>a Caribe]]'' to reach number one on the [[Latin Pop Albums]] chart; it reached its peak in the week ending 8 September 2007.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/latin-pop-albums?chartDate=2007-09-08 Latin Pop Albums]. ''Billboard''. Nielsen Business Media. Retrieved on 5 May 2012.</ref> On the Latin Albums chart, ''Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer'' debuted at number two.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/latin-albums?chartDate=2007-09-08 Latin Pop Albums]. ''Billboard''. Nielsen Business Media. Retrieved on 5 May 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/latin-albums?chartDate=2005-12-24 Latin Pop Albums]. ''Billboard''. Nielsen Business Media. Retrieved on 5 May 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/latin-albums?chartDate=2002-12-21 Latin Pop Albums]. ''Billboard''. Nielsen Business Media. Retrieved on 5 May 2012.</ref> The album was commercially successful in Latin America, and was certified [[Gold certification|Gold]] in Venezuela, Uruguay, Colombia, Chile, and Peru;<ref name=adn1>[http://www.adnmundo.com/contenidos/adncool/ricardo_arjona_quien_dijo_ayer_tour_gira_co070907.html "Ricardo Arjona presenta `<U+00BF>Qui<U+00E9>n dijo ayer?' en Colombia y Venezuela"]. ADN Mundo. Retrieved 3 October 2011.</ref> and [[Platinum certification|Platinum]] in Argentina, Mexico and the United States.<ref name=adn1/><ref>[http://www.somosfans.com/2007/09/04/%C2%BFquien-dijo-ayer-de-ricardo-arjona-ya-es-disco-de-oro-y-platino/ "<U+00BF>Qui<U+00E9>n dijo ayer? De Ricardo Arjona ya es disco de Oro y Platino"]. ''SomosFans.com''. Retrieved 03 October 2011.</ref><ref>The US certification for Platinum is for Latin albums, which means 100,000 copies.</ref>

